        <a href="/loading-video.mp4">link to the video</a> instead.
      </video>
    </p>
    <p>
      This hurts user experience â€“
      <a href="https://3perf.com/talks/web-perf-101/#perf-importance-header">and affects business metrics</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      In 2017-2018, most browsers released support for
      <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/@font-face/font-display"><code>font-display</code></a>,
      a CSS feature that helps to configure that behavior. For example,
      with <code>font-display: swap</code>, the text is rendered immediately
      using a fallback font. Then, when a custom font is downloaded, the text
      is re-rendered in that font.
    </p>
    <p>
      Unfortunately, Google Fonts
      <a href="https://github.com/google/fonts/issues/358">donâ€™t support <code>font-display</code> natively</a>, so you
      canâ€™t apply this optimization to them. This tool generates a
      small wrapper around Google Fonts that adds
      <code>font-display</code> support and helps to render text quicker.
    </p>
    <h2>How does this work?</h2>
    <p>
      The generated code snippet:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>downloads the Google Fonts stylesheet asynchronously,</li>
      <li>patches it to insert the <code>font-display</code> declaration,</li>
      <li>and inserts that stylesheet into the document.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The snippet should work fine in older browsers. It uses
      <a href="https://github.com/bramstein/fontfaceobserver/issues/62#issuecomment-398399886">the
        <code>window.FontFace</code> check</a>
      to detect if a browser supports <code>font-display</code>. If the
      browser doesnâ€™t support <code>font-display</code>, or if
      <code>window.FontFace</code> is not available, the script falls back to
      inserting a regular <code>&lt;link> tag</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The snippet doesnâ€™t cause unnecessary font jumps. If the Google Fonts
      stylesheet is already cached, the script will insert it into the
      document synchronously â€“ so that the browser can apply custom fonts
      immediately.
    </p>
    <h2>How does this affect performance?</h2>
    <p>
      The snippet tries to be as lightweight as possible. To achieve performance
      similar to the original <code>&lt;link rel="stylesheet"></code>, this
      snippet generator:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        generates a <code>&lt;link rel="preload"></code> tag for the stylesheet
        so the browser starts downloading it as soon as possible,
      </li>
      <li>
        generates a <code>&lt;link rel="preconnect"></code> tag
        for the domain font files are loaded from (and <code>&lt;link rel="dns-prefetch"></code>
        for older browsers) â€“ so the browser can fetch font files sooner,
      </li>
      <li>
        and provides an inline script instead of an external one â€“ to avoid
        making an extra HTTP request
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Because the snippet has to use <code>&lt;link rel="preload" as="fetch"></code> â€“
